Forecasting model

Zoey Werbin, Ryan Quinn, Steve Gougherty, Yetianjian Wang

3/29/2019

In this markdown document, well run through a forecast using our dynamic linear models for the historical data from 5 NEON sites. We will model the ratio of bacteria and archaea (as one combined group) to fungi. Our current covariates are daily precipitation and minimum daily temperature, both averaged to the month level.

Lets look at our JAGS model code. Were including random effects for each sampling date, and fixed effects of minimum temperature and precipitation. In the missing data model, we pull from distributions of our covariates; precipitation has a gamma distribution, because we cant have negative values, but temperature has a Normal distribution because negative values are fine. We have uninformative precisions drawn from a gamma distribution with shape and rate of 0.1.

ourmodel <- "  model{
  
#### Priors
x[1] ~ dnorm(x_ic,tau_ic)
tau_obs ~ dgamma(a_obs,r_obs)
tau_add ~ dgamma(a_add,r_add)

#### Random Effects
  tau_alpha~dgamma(0.1,0.1)
  for(i in 1:n){                  
  alpha[i]~dnorm(0,tau_alpha)
  }

#### Fixed Effects
beta_IC~dnorm(0,0.001)
betaIntercept~dnorm(0,0.001)
betaTmin~dnorm(0,0.001)
betaPrecip~dgamma(0.01,0.01)
muTmin~dnorm(0,0.001)
muPrecip~dnorm(0,0.001)
tauTmin~dgamma(0.01,0.01)
tauPrecip~dgamma(0.01,0.01)


#### Data Model
for(t in 1:n){
OBS[t] ~ dnorm(x[t],tau_obs)
Z[t,2] ~ dnorm(muTmin,tauTmin)
Z[t,3] ~ dnorm(muPrecip,tauPrecip)
}

#### Process Model
for(t in 2:n){
mu[t] <- beta_IC*x[t-1]  + betaIntercept*Z[t,1] + betaTmin*Z[t,2] + betaPrecip*Z[t,3] + alpha[t[i]]
x[t]~dnorm(mu[t],tau_add)
}

}"

Heres the function well use for our forecast, analogous to the process model in our JAGS code:

# our function
forecastN <- function(IC,betaIntercept,alpha,betaPrecip,beta_IC,ppt,Q=0,n=Nmc) {
  N <- matrix(NA,n,NT)  ## storage
  Nprev <- IC           ## initialize
  N[,1] <- Nprev
  for(t in 2:NT){
      mu = beta_IC*Nprev + betaIntercept*1 + betaPrecip*ppt[,t] + alpha  
      N[,t] <- rlnorm(n,log(mu),Q)  
      Nprev <- N[,t]        ## update IC
  }
  return(N)
}

plot.run <- function(){
  sel = seq(1,10)
  plot(time,time,type='n',ylim=c(4,31), ylab="N")
  ecoforecastR::ciEnvelope(time1,ci[1,sel],ci[3,sel],col=col.alpha("lightBlue",0.6))
  lines(time1,ci[2,sel],col="blue")
  points(time1,log(STER[,"ratio"]))
}

We dont have a random site effect because our model isnt hierarchical. Were just looking at one NEON site (STER) right now. So lets go ahead and partition the variance!

### calculation of variances
varI     <- apply(N.I,2,var, na.rm=T)
varIP    <- apply(N.IP,2,var, na.rm=T)
varIPD   <- apply(N.IPD,2,var, na.rm=T)
varIPDE  <- apply(N.IPDE,2,var, na.rm=T)
#varIPDEA <- apply(N.IPDEA,2,var) # we only have one site
varMat   <- rbind(varI,varIP,varIPD,varIPDE)#,varIPDEA)

## in-sample stacked area plot
V.pred.rel.in <- apply(varMat[-5,],2,function(x) {x/max(x)})
plot(time2,V.pred.rel.in[1,],ylim=c(0,1),type='n',main="Relative Variance: In-Sample",ylab="Proportion of Variance",xlab="time")
ciEnvelope(time2,rep(0,ncol(V.pred.rel.in)),V.pred.rel.in[1,],col=N.cols[1])
ciEnvelope(time2,V.pred.rel.in[1,],V.pred.rel.in[2,],col=N.cols[2])
ciEnvelope(time2,V.pred.rel.in[2,],V.pred.rel.in[3,],col=N.cols[3])
ciEnvelope(time2,V.pred.rel.in[3,],V.pred.rel.in[4,],col=N.cols[4])
legend("topright",legend=c("Process","Driver","Parameter","InitCond"),col=rev(N.cols[-5]),lty=1,lwd=5)

We have almost no driver or parameter uncertainty (driver uncertainty is there, but for some reason being masked by process error. Parameter uncertainty looks like it was too small to plot.)
